

                           Videogame Console Notes
                        =============================

                 Created: January 2005    Updated: Nov. 2005


   Amiga 500 . . . . . . . - When it was first launched many Amiga 500
                             packs contained a note for the Amiga 500Plus,
                             telling users about the upgraded machine.

   Amiga 1200+ / 2200. . . - Sold only in the USA, it is said to be a
                             A1200 with the 68030 CPU. Detailed specs
                             are unknown - most likely it was an A1200
                             which came pre-equipped with an accelerator
                             card.
                             However 'A1200` and 'A1300` were also
                             codenames for early Walker prototypes, an
                             AA/68EC030-system built by Amiga Technologies.

   C64 . . . . . . . . . . - Commodore 64.
                             Commodore 64 Compendium

   C116. . . . . . . . . . - Commodore 116 began it's life back in 1984
                             when it was shown at the summer CES show
                             (Consumer Electronics Show), in Vegas?
                             The computer is a cut-down version of the
                             +4 and has a rubber keyboard.
                             It is said to be the cheapest Commodore
                             ever made. The CPU is a 7501 and runs on
                             Commodore BASIC 3.5. It is now a rare
                             machine as it was only sold in Germany
                             and some East European countries.

   COLECO. . . . . . . . . - CO-LE-CO.... Connecticut Leather Company.
                             1960 - Worlds largest manufacturer of
                                    above-ground swimming pools.
                             1976 - Got into computers with the
                                    Telstar Arcade machine.
                             1983 - ADAM launched in the US, in October.

   DIAL-UP . . . . . . . . - A way to connect to the internet via the
                             humble modem.

   GAME BOY MICRO . . . .  - Smaller version of the Game Boy Advance.
                             Exact size is 4 inches by 2 inches!

                             Japan launch date - 13th September 2005
                             US launch date - ??
                             UK/Europe launch date - 4th Nov. 2005

   ISDN . . . . . . . . . .- ISDN predated ADSL and was somewhat faster
                             than the modem.

   JIFFYDOS . . . . . . . .- JiffyDOS is by Creative Designs Inc.
                             You needed a hardware fix for both the
                             Commodore 64 and drive to run it.
                             The C64's 1581 drive can be used with it.

   MODEM . . . . . . . . . - Modem is named as it both Modulates and
                             Demodulates the data as it's sent/received
                             to/from the phone line.

   NINTENDO DS . . . . . . - Nintendo handheld with 2 screens, one (on the
                             bottom) is touch-sensitive. Also features
                             WI-FI communication.

                             US launch date - 21st November 2004
                             UK/Europe launch date - 11th March 2005
                             Australia launch date - 24th February 2005
                             Japan launch date - ??

   NINTENDO ENTERTAINMENT  - The NES (Famicom - for Family Computer - in
             SYSTEM (NES)    Japan) was Nintendo's first games console.
                             In the UK the NES was made by Mattel (?!) and
                             distributed by Bandai UK.

   PODCASTING. . . . . . . - Podcasting is a blanket term used to describe
                             a collection of technologies for automatically
                             distributing audio and video programmes over
                             the internet via a publish and subscribe
                             model.
                             Podcasting enables independant producers to
                             create self-published syndicated "radio shows"
                             and gives broadcast radio or television
                             programmes a new distribution method.

                           (Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Podcast )

                             Amipodder enables you to subscribe (for free)
                             to podcast feeds on your Amiga:

                             http://www.seal-amiga.co.uk/robert/amipodder/

                             There is also an excellent podcast client for
                             the Amiga written by Robert Williams.
                             Marco Iannaccone is working on a forthcoming
                             video podcast about Amiga issues, and Robert
                             Williams is going to issue a new version of
                             Amipodder which handles both video and audio
                             podcasts.

   RADIO SHACKS TRS-80 . . - The TRS-80 was made by Radio Shack in the
                             late 1970s and early 1980s.

          TRS-80 Model 100 - 4 AA batteries to run
                    (1983) - Ports for printers, RS-232C, cassette and
                             6V DC current
                           - ROM Max 64KB (2 banks fo 32KB)
                           - ROM module expansion compartment
                           - RAM Max 32KB
                           - TELCOM ability
                           - Has built-in modem
                           - LCD display: 240 x 64 Full Dot Matrix

   SEGA COMPUTER 3000      - See SG1000.
   (SC-3000)

   SEGA CDX . . . . . . . .- The Sega CDX has a CD drive in the front
                             for MegaCD (aka Sega CD) games with a 
                             cartridge slot directly behind it for
                             MegaDrive games.

   SEGA GAME 1000          - One of Sega's first consoles, only released
   (SG-1000)                 in Japan.

   SEGA GAME GEAR . . . . .- Handheld released around 1992. It had a
                             colour pallette of 64 colours, but the 6
                             batteries only lasted 4-5 hours.

   SEGA MARK III           - See SG1000.
   (SG-1000 II)

   SEGA NOMAD . . . . . . .- Handheld MegaDrive that was only released
                             in the USA around 1996 and plays the full
                             size MegaDrive games.

   SEGA PICO               - Childs gaming toy.
   (MK-49002)                http://www.vidgame.net/SEGA/pico.htm

   SEGA SUPER CONTROL STATION - See SG1000.
   (SF-7000)

   SUPER NINTENDO . . . .  - The Nintendo Entertainment System or SNES
      ENTERTAINMENT SYSTEM   (Super Famicom in Japan) was Nintendo's
            (SNES)           2nd games console and was based around
                             a "wacky" 8-bit processor which is
                             responsible for the Mode 7 scrolling grounds
                             in such games as Mario Kart and F-Zero.

   SONY PSP . . . . . . .  - Sony's first handheld is the PSP (Playstation
                             Portable), and uses a new disc format created
                             by Sony - UMD (Ultimate Media Disc).

                             Japan launch date - 12th December 2004
                             US launch date - March 2005
                             UK/Europe launch date - 1st Sept. 2005

   USB . . . . . . . . . . - Universal Serial Bus.
                             Usually found on modern PC's & Amiga One.

                              --- End File ---

